In this article, President Obama proclaims February 2016 as National Teen Dating Violence Awareness and Prevention Month. He highlights the seriousness of teen dating violence, which can take various forms, including physical, sexual, or emotional abuse, and can occur in person or through electronic communication and social media. The president emphasizes the detrimental effects of violent dating relationships, such as depression, anxiety, substance abuse, and thoughts of suicide. He calls for educating youth about the dangers and consequences of dating violence and reaffirms the basic human right to be free from violence and abuse. The article also mentions that dating violence can occur in any relationship and that anyone can experience it, regardless of gender, race, religion, ethnicity, sexual orientation, or socioeconomic status. President Obama discusses the efforts of his administration to address teen dating violence, including Vice President Joe Biden's 1is2many initiative and the establishment of the White House Task Force to Protect Students from Sexual Assault. He calls on all Americans to support efforts in their communities and schools to empower young people to develop healthy relationships and engage in activities that prevent and respond to teen dating violence. The article provides contact information for immediate and confidential support for those involved in an abusive relationship.